Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js Project

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project using the App Router, following the latest official documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version ^2.0.1 using npm
- Updated package.json and package-lock.json to include the new dependency

### 2. Analytics Integration
Modified `app/layout.tsx`:
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component before the closing `</body>` tag in the root layout
- Preserved all existing code structure, styling, and functionality

## Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel documentation for Next.js App Router projects:
- The Analytics component was added to the root layout file (app/layout.tsx)
- Component placed at the end of the body element to ensure it doesn't block page rendering
- Used the Next.js-specific import path (`@vercel/analytics/next`) for optimal integration

## Verification

✅ Package installed successfully (428 packages added)
✅ Linter passed with no errors on modified file
✅ TypeScript types are correct (Analytics component is properly typed)
✅ Code follows existing project patterns and conventions
✅ All changes preserve existing functionality

## Files Modified
- `app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics import and component
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree

## Next Steps
To activate Web Analytics:
1. Deploy the project to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under the Analytics tab
3. Monitor the Network tab for requests to `/<unique-path>/view` to confirm tracking is active

Note: Analytics will only track page views when deployed to Vercel. Local development does not send analytics data.
